[5] Cholera - China: (Wuhan, Hubei) O139, seafood market
Date: Fri 15 Jul 2022
Source: Global Times [edited]
https://www.globaltimes.cn/page/202207/1270609.shtml


Wuhan in Central China's Hubei Province reported on Thu 14 Jul 2022 that 4 seafood samples tested positive for the O139 type of bacteria that cause cholera. Officials say this is unrelated to the previously confirmed case found at Wuhan University [see report above]. Personnel and the environment involved with the positive samples have not shown abnormalities after examination, authorities said.

The 4 turtle samples contaminated with the virus were found on Wed, 13 Jul 2022, during a daily health inspection work at the Baishazhou Market in Wuhan, local authorities said in a notice issued the next day. An emergency response was immediately launched to conduct an epidemiological survey, environmental sampling, and disinfection. The shop selling the products has been temporarily shut down for 3 days, and the contaminated products have been properly disposed of. Persons in contact with the samples all returned negative results for cholera bacterium.

Personnel and environment involved with the positive samples have not shown abnormalities after examination, authorities said, and they have reminded other destinations outside of Wuhan that received relevant products of the same batch.

There exist some risks of the cholera bacteria in these products infecting humans, experts noted but said there is no need to panic. "Cholera is an infection of the digestive tract. So as long as people eat cooked products, there would be no risk of infection," Yang Zhanqiu, deputy director of the pathogen biology department at Wuhan University, told the Global Times on Fri, 15 Jul 2022. Even if people are infected with cholera, China has long been capable of treating the disease with drugs and other medical facilities, Yang said. The incident has not been found to have involved people and is unrelated to the confirmed case of cholera discovered at Wuhan University on 9 Jul 2022. The patient showed symptoms of vomiting and diarrhea accompanied by fever and quickly recovered after effective diagnosis and treatment. No other cases were reported.

Cholera in China has been under control since 2000 and only sporadic cases have been reported in recent years. China can provide advanced medical treatment and efficacious medicines against the disease, thus it is less likely to see a cholera outbreak nowadays, experts said, noting that there is no need to panic.

[byline: Fan Anqi]

--
communicated by:
ProMED

