[6] Cholera - India: (Amravati, Maharashtra)
Date: Thu 14 Jul 2022
Source: Mint [edited]
https://www.livemint.com/news/india/cholera-outbreak-in-this-maharashtra-district-claims-5-lives-total-cases-at-181-11657763710740.html


In the Amravati district of Maharashtra, 5 people have died due to the waterborne disease, cholera. Cholera broke out in the Chikhaldara and Amravati blocks of the Amravati district on 7 Jul 2022. So far, as many as 181 patients have been diagnosed with the disease, the state public health department confirmed. Among the deceased, 2 were women and 3 were men. 3 of these patients were in the age group 24 to 40 years and 2 were over 70 years old. The ongoing outbreak is in 3 villages in the Chikhaldara block (Dongri, Koylari, and Ghana) and 1 village (Naya Akola) in Amaravati block.

As per the state government, medical teams are working round the clock in outbreak-affected villages, and efforts for prevention and control in terms of water quality monitoring, patient surveillance, management and treatment, and health awareness are underway. A state-level squad is currently in the district to investigate the outbreak and provide appropriate guidance.

Meanwhile, Maharashtra has been witnessing heavy rainfall for the past week, resulting in waterlogging in several areas. The India Meteorological Department (IMD) has issued an Orange Alert for Mumbai, Raigad, Ratnagiri, Sindhudurg, Kolhapur, Satara, Amravati, and Thane while a red alert has been issued in Palghar, Nashik, and Pune.

